# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1975-cricket-world-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The **1912 Triangular Tournament** was a Test cricket competition played between Australia, England and South Africa, the only Test-playing nations at the time.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The ultimate winners of the tournament were England, with four wins in their six matches, but the tournament was deemed a failure, with disappointing crowds and uncompetitive cricket, caused in part by a weakened Australia team.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The tournament was the first tournament in Test history to be played between more than two nations.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] It was the only such tournament until the Asian Test Championships of 1998–99 and 2001–02, and the ICC World Test Championship which began in 2019.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The idea of a competition involving all three of the nations then playing Test cricket (Australia, England and South Africa) was proposed at the first meeting of the Imperial Cricket Conference in July 1909.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The original proposal was for a tournament to be held every four years, with the first hosted by England in 1912.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] For a variety of reasons, the tournament was not a success.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The summer was one of the wettest since records began in 1766: rainfall in the three months of June, July and August was more than twice the seasonal average, and August, 1912, was the coolest, dullest and wettest August of the 20th century.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] At that time, pitches were not covered to protect them against rain, so the batsmen were at a distinct disadvantage on the proverbial sticky wicket.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] These problems were exacerbated since Tests in England were in those days played over three days rather than the five days that is now usual.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] In addition, disputes between the players and management in Australia meant that six leading Australian players refused to tour whilst medical duties meant “Ranji” Hordern, easily Australia’s best bowler in the 1911–12 Ashes series, could not tour either.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] These setbacks severely weakened a team that had otherwise been level with England in recent Ashes series.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The leg spin and googly bowlers in the South African team were very effective on the matting pitches then in use in South Africa, but were less deadly on English grass pitches.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] As a result, England dominated, winning four of their six matches and drawing the other two.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The tournament was so unsuccessful that it has never been repeated.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The idea of a tournament of international cricket matches between more than two countries was not repeated, outside of regional tournaments in East Africa and the West Indies, until the invention of One Day International cricket and the first Women's Cricket World Cup in 1973.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The only other Test cricket tournaments in history were the Asian Test Championships played in 1998–99 and 2001–02, which were also not great successes, until the ICC World Test Championship began in 2019.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] Perhaps the most notable incident of the series was Australian bowler Jimmy Matthews taking two hat-tricks in the same Test match, one in each innings of the opening match against South Africa, the only time a bowler has taken two hat-tricks in the same Test.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The **1966 FIFA World Cup** was the eighth FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial football tournament for senior national teams.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] It was played in England from 11 to 30 July 1966.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] England defeated West Germany 4–2 in the final to win their first, and so far only, World Cup title.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The final was level at 2–2 after 90 minutes and went into extra time, during which Geoff Hurst scored two goals to complete his hat-trick, the first to be scored in a World Cup final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Portuguese striker Eusébio was the tournament's top scorer, with nine goals earning him the golden boot award with three goals more than second placed Helmut Haller.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] It was the first World Cup held in the English-speaking world.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] England were the fifth nation to win the event, and the third host nation to win after Uruguay in 1930 and Italy in 1934.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Reigning world champions Brazil failed to get past the group stages as they were defeated by Hungary and Portugal.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] It was the second time that defending champions were eliminated in the group stages after Italy in 1950.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] This would not occur again until 36 years later.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The two debut teams performed well at the competition – North Korea beat Italy 1–0 on the way to reaching the quarter-finals, where they lost to Portugal 5–3 after leading 3–0.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Portugal themselves finished third, beating Soviet Union 2–1 in the bronze-match.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] During the qualifying games, FIFA, citing logistic and competitive reasons, announced that there would be no direct qualifying place for an African team: all 15 African nations who had entered immediately boycotted the competition in protest.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Matches were played at eight stadiums across England, foremost Wembley Stadium, which had a capacity of 98,600.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] It was at Wembley that England played all its matches; that the tournament was opened by Queen Elizabeth II; and where the final was played.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Prior to the tournament, the Jules Rimet trophy was stolen, but was recovered by a dog named Pickles four months before the tournament began.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] It was the first World Cup to have selected matches broadcast via satellite to countries on other continents.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The final, which was broadcast locally by the BBC, was the last to be shown entirely in black and white.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] This was also the only World Cup in history that did not have matches on Sundays, owing to religious laws at the time, which were repealed ten years later in 1976.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] England was chosen as host nation for the 1966 World Cup in Rome, Italy, on 22 August 1960, over rival bids from West Germany and Spain.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] It was the first tournament to be held in a country that was affected directly by World War II, as the four previous tournaments were held either in countries out of war theatres or in neutral countries.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Despite the Africans' absence, there was another new record number of entries for the qualifying tournament, with 70 nations taking part.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] FIFA determined that ten teams from Europe would qualify, along with four from South America, one from Asia and one from North and Central America.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Portugal and North Korea qualified for the first time.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The following 16 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The mascot for the 1966 competition was "World Cup Willie", a cartoon lion wearing a Union Jack jersey emblazoned with the words "WORLD CUP".
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] This was the first World Cup mascot, and one of the first mascots to be associated with a major sporting competition.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Willie was designed by freelance children's book illustrator Reg Hoye.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The official match ball was produced by Slazenger for the tournament.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The Confederation of African Football (CAF) considered that the lack of direct representation of African nations in the World Cup was unfair, and demanded that FIFA guarantee at least one African nation a place in the finals of the following tournament.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] They also protested against the readmission of South Africa to FIFA in 1963, despite their expulsion from CAF because of the country's apartheid regime in 1958.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] As a result of this boycott, FIFA fined CAF 5,000 Swiss francs.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Yidnekatchew Tessema, then president of the CAF, responded to this punishment by saying, "FIFA has adopted a relentless attitude against the African Associations and its decisions resemble methods of intimidation and repression designed to discourage any further impulses of a similar nature.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] South Africa was subsequently assigned to the Asia and Oceania qualifying group, before being disqualified after being suspended again due to pressure from other African nations in October 1964.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Despite this, FIFA refused to change the qualifying format, citing competitive and logistical issues, and the African teams withdrew in protest.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] CAF subsequently informed FIFA that they would refuse to participate in World Cup qualifying for the 1970 tournament unless at least one African team had an automatic place assured in the World Cup: this was put in place for the 1970 FIFA World Cup, and all subsequent World Cup finals.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Players from the Portuguese African colonies of Angola and Mozambique participated for Portugal.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The United Kingdom, which had fought for South Korea in the Korean War, was concerned over the entry of North Korea in the tournament.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The UK did not recognise North Korea and feared that its presence would strain relations with South Korea and the United States.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] FIFA told England's Football Association that the tournament would be moved if any qualified team were to be refused entry.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] On the suggestion of the British Foreign Office, the playing of national anthems, and meetings between players and state figures such as Queen Elizabeth II, would take place in only two games: the opening game and the final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] North Korea was not scheduled for the former, and was considered unlikely to reach the latter.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] A Foreign Office suggestion for flags outside stadiums to be removed after each team's elimination, in the expectation of an early North Korean exit, was vetoed by the Department of Education and Science.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The 1966 World Cup had a rather unusual hero off the field, a dog called Pickles.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In the build-up to the tournament, the Jules Rimet trophy was stolen from an exhibition display.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] It was discovered wrapped in newspaper as the dog sniffed under bushes in a London garden.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The FA commissioned a replica cup in case the original cup was not found in time.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] This replica, as well as Pickles' collar, is held at the National Football Museum in Manchester, where it is on display.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] West Germany encouraged and covered up a culture of doping across many sports for decades.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] A 2013 report by researchers at Berlin's Humboldt University on behalf of the German Olympic Sports Confederation, titled "Doping in Germany from 1950 to today", linked the West Germany national team of 1966, which reached the World Cup final, with doping.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] While refereeing controversies are common in World Cup history, the 1966 tournament stands out because of the structural reforms it provoked.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] A series of violent matches and contentious dismissals led FIFA to introduce major changes to the Laws of the Game in the following tournament.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The tournament was marked by persistently rough play and inconsistent officiating.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In their opening match, Brazilian star Pelé was repeatedly fouled and left the pitch injured after a strong tackle to the knee, forcing him to miss the subsequent match against Hungary.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Upon returning for the final group stage clash with Portugal, Pelé suffered two heavy challenges from Portuguese defenders, most notably João Morais, that ended his tournament.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Pelé departed on a stretcher, and Brazil exited the competition 3–1.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Morais was allowed to remain on the pitch.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] No players were sent off in any of those games.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In another quarter-final between West Germany and Uruguay, shortly after halftime, Uruguayan players Horacio Troche and Héctor Silva were both dismissed by English referee Jim Finney.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay conceded 3 goals when reduced to nine men and South American media decried a pattern of European referee bias.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In light of these high-profile incidents, FIFA recognised the need for clearer disciplinary procedures and greater consistency in officiating.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Ahead of the 1970 World Cup, the yellow and red card system was introduced, alongside the allowance of two substitutions per team and new efforts to standardise referee training and interpretations of the Laws of the Game.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In 2008, Brazilian FIFA president from 1974 til 1998, João Havelange, accused this competition, along with the 1974 FIFA World Cup in West Germany for being fixed to benefit the host country.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] According to him Brazil deserved to win in both cases.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The format of the 1966 competition remained the same as in 1962: 16 qualified teams were divided into four groups of four.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Two points were awarded for a win and one point for a draw, with goal average and eventually drawing lots used to separate teams equal on points.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The top two teams in each group advanced to the knockout stage.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In the knockout games, if the teams were tied after 90 minutes, 30 minutes of extra time were played.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] For any match other than the final, if the teams were still tied after extra time, lots would be drawn to determine the winner.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The final would have been replayed if tied after extra time; but if still tied after the replay, the champion would have been decided by drawing lots.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In the event, no replays or drawing of lots were necessary.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The draw for the final tournament took place on 6 January 1966 at the Royal Garden Hotel in London, and was the first to be televised.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The seeded teams for the draw were England, West Germany, Brazil, and Italy.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Eight venues were used for this World Cup.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The newest and biggest venue used was Wembley Stadium in north west London, which was 43 years old in 1966.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] As was often the case in the World Cup, group matches were played in two venues close to each other.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The group stage match between Uruguay and France played at White City Stadium (originally built for the 1908 Summer Olympics) was scheduled for a Friday, the same day as regularly scheduled greyhound racing at Wembley.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Because Wembley's owner refused to cancel this, the game had to be moved to the alternative venue in London.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Group 2's matches were played at Hillsborough Stadium in Sheffield and Villa Park in Birmingham; Group 3's matches were played at Old Trafford in Manchester and Goodison Park in Liverpool; and Group 4's matches were played at Ayresome Park in Middlesbrough and Roker Park in Sunderland.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The stadium construction cost are estimated to be today's equivalent of £9.2 million, additional to £36.22 million for tournament organisation.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The most used venue was Wembley, which was used for nine matches, including all six featuring England, the final and the match for third place.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Goodison Park was used for five matches, Roker Park and Hillsborough both hosted four, while Old Trafford, Villa Park and Ayresome Park each hosted three matches and did not host any knockout round matches.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The opening match took place on Monday, 11 July, which made it the second World Cup after 1930 not to begin in May or June.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Before the tournament began, eventual winners England were 9/2 second favourites with bookmakers behind Brazil (9/4), while beaten finalists West Germany were 25/1 outsiders.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The final took place on Saturday, 30 July 1966, the 36th anniversary of the first final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Until 2022, this was the latest date that any tournament had concluded.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The reason for the unusually late scheduling of the tournament appears to lie with the outside broadcast commitments of the BBC, which also had to cover the Wimbledon tennis tournament (which ran between 20 June and 2 July) and the Open Golf Championship (6 to 9 July).
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] 1966 was a World Cup with few goals as the teams began to play much more tactically and defensively.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] This was exemplified by Alf Ramsey's England as they finished top of Group 1 with only four goals, but having none scored against them.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] They also became the first World Cup winning team not to win its first game in the tournament.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay were the other team to qualify from that group at the expense of both Mexico and France.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] All the group's matches were played at Wembley Stadium apart from the match between Uruguay and France which took place at White City Stadium.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In Group 2, West Germany and Argentina qualified with ease as they each finished the group with 5 points, Spain managed 2, while Switzerland left the competition after losing all three group matches.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] FIFA cautioned Argentina for its violent style in the group games, particularly in the scoreless draw with West Germany, which saw Argentinean Rafael Albrecht get sent off and suspended for the next match.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In the northwest of England, Old Trafford and Goodison Park played host to Group 3 which saw the two-time defending champions Brazil finish in third place behind Portugal and Hungary, and be eliminated along with Bulgaria.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Brazil were defeated 3–1 by Hungary in a classic encounter before falling by the same scoreline to Portugal in a controversial game.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Portugal appeared in the finals for the first time, and made quite an impact.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] They won all three of their games in the group stage, with a lot of help from their outstanding striker Eusébio, whose nine goals made him the tournament's top scorer.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Group 4, however, provided the biggest upset when North Korea beat Italy 1–0 at Ayresome Park, Middlesbrough and finished above them, thus earning qualification to the next round along with the Soviet Union.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] This was the first time that a nation from outside Europe or the Americas had progressed from the first stage of a World Cup: the next would be Morocco in 1986.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] It appeared as if the surprise package North Korea would claim another major upset in their match against Portugal at Goodison Park: they led 3–0 after 22 minutes.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] It fell to one of the greatest stars of the tournament, Eusébio, to change that.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] He scored four goals in the game and José Augusto added a fifth goal in the 78th minute to earn Portugal a 5–3 victory.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Meanwhile, in the other two games, Ferenc Bene's late goal for Hungary against the Soviet Union, who were led by Lev Yashin's stellar goalkeeping, proved little more than a consolation as they crashed out 2–1, and the only goal between Argentina and England came courtesy of England's Geoff Hurst.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] During that controversial game (for more details see Argentina and England football rivalry), Argentina's Antonio Rattín became the first player to be sent off in a senior international football match at Wembley.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Rattín at first refused to leave the field and eventually had to be escorted by several policemen.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Scoreless when Rattin was dismissed, the game was decided by Hurst's headed goal twelve minutes from the end of normal time.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] This game is called *el robo del siglo* (lit.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] 'the robbery of the century') in Argentina.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Bobby Charlton scored both goals in England's win, with Portugal's goal coming from a penalty in the 82nd minute after a handball by Jack Charlton on the goal line.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The other semi-final also finished 2–1: Franz Beckenbauer scoring the winning goal with a left foot shot from the edge of the area for West Germany as they beat the Soviet Union.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Portugal went on to beat the Soviet Union 2–1 to take third place.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Portugal's third place was the best finish by a team making its World Cup debut since 1934.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] London's Wembley Stadium was the venue for the final, and 98,000 people attended.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] After 12 minutes 32 seconds Helmut Haller put West Germany ahead, but the score was levelled by Geoff Hurst four minutes later.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Martin Peters put England in the lead in the 78th minute; England looked set to claim the title when the referee awarded a free kick to West Germany with one minute left.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The ball was launched goalward and Wolfgang Weber scored, with England appealing in vain for handball as the ball came through the crowded penalty area.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] With the score level at 2–2 at the end of 90 minutes, the game went to extra time.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In the 98th minute, Hurst found himself on the scoresheet again; his shot hit the crossbar, bounced down onto the goal line, and was awarded as a goal.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Debate has long raged over whether the ball crossed the line, with the goal becoming part of World Cup history.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] England's final goal was scored by Hurst again, as a celebratory pitch invasion began.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] This made Geoff Hurst the first player to have scored three times in a single World Cup final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] BBC commentator Kenneth Wolstenholme's description of the match's closing moments has gone down in history: "Some people are on the pitch.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] England's total of eleven goals scored in six games set a new record low for average goals per game scored by a World Cup winning team.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The record stood until 1982, when it was surpassed by Italy's 12 goals in seven games; in 2010 this record was lowered again by Spain, winning the Cup with eight goals in seven games.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] England's total of three goals conceded also constituted a record low for average goals per game conceded by a World Cup winning team.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] That record stood until 1994, when it was surpassed by Brazil's three goals in seven games.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] France again lowered the record to two goals in seven during the 1998 tournament, a record that has since been equalled by Italy at the 2006 tournament and by Spain's two goals conceded during the 2010 tournament.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] England received the recovered Jules Rimet trophy from Queen Elizabeth II and were crowned World Cup winners for the first time.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In this World Cup, the national anthems were played only in the final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] They were not played in the earlier matches because the organisers (FIFA and the FA) feared that North Korea's presence – a socialist country that was not recognised by the United Kingdom – in the World Cup would cause problems with South Korea.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] A memo from the Foreign Office months before the finals began stated that the solution would be "denying the visas to North Korean players".
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] The final, held at Wembley Stadium, was the last whose television broadcast was in black and white.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] A total of 26 match referees and other officials featured at the event.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Despite the event being a worldwide tournament, the majority of the officials were from Europe.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Gottfried Dienst refereed the final between England and West Germany.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] With nine goals, Eusébio was the top scorer in the tournament.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In total, 89 goals were scored by 47 players, with two of them credited as own goals.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] Angola and Mozambique represented Portugal.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1966-fifa-world-cup] In 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1970-71-ashes-series] The **England cricket team** toured Australia in the 1970–71 season to play a six-match Test series against Australia for The Ashes.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1970-71-ashes-series] The tour was organised by the Marylebone Cricket Club and the team played non-Test matches under the MCC name.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1970-71-ashes-series] The Third Test at Melbourne was abandoned without a ball being bowled.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1970-71-ashes-series] England's captain Ray Illingworth had won the toss and decided to field but rain began at that point and eventually caused the abandonment.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1970-71-ashes-series] The game was replaced by the first-ever Limited Overs International on what should have been the final day of the Test Match.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1970-71-ashes-series] Despite misgivings on the part of the England team, it was decided to stage a 7th Test so that the full complement of six matches could be completed.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1970-71-ashes-series] England won the series 2–0 with four matches drawn and one abandoned, so England regained The Ashes for the first time since 1959.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1970-71-ashes-series] The first-ever limited overs international came about by chance, being hastily arranged to take place on what should have been the final day of the abandoned Third Test.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The **1973 Women's Cricket World Cup** was the inaugural Women's Cricket World Cup, held in England from 20 June to 28 July 1973.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] It was the first tournament of its kind, held two years before the first limited overs World Cup for men in 1975.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The competition was won by the hosts, England.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The competition was the brainchild of businessman Sir Jack Hayward, who contributed £40,000 towards its costs.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England, Australia, New Zealand, Trinidad and Tobago and Jamaica were joined by an International XI and a Young England team in a round-robin league which saw the team with the most points win the World Cup.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England topped the group with 20 points from their six matches, including five victories and one defeat, while Australia were runners up posting 17 points with four wins.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The final round-robin match, held at Edgbaston on 28 July, was distinguished by a commanding century by Enid Bakewell of England, whose 118 formed the bedrock of England's imposing 279/3 in their 60 overs, with captain Rachael Heyhoe Flint scoring 64.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Australia were restricted by tight England bowling and fell well short of their target, scoring 187/9.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The cup was presented by Princess Anne and the winning England team were hosted at a reception at 10 Downing Street by Prime Minister Edward Heath.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Bakewell, one of England's finest all time players, was the leading run-scorer in the competition with 264 runs while Rosalind Heggs, of Young England, was the leading wicket-taker with 12 wickets.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The next World Cup was held five years later in 1978.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1974-english-cricket-season] The **1974 English cricket season** was the 75th in which the County Championship had been an official competition.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1974-english-cricket-season] The recent pattern of joint tours continued with India and Pakistan again playing three Tests each against England.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1974-english-cricket-season] Worcestershire won the County Championship.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-county-championship] The **1975 County Championship** was the 76th officially organised running of the County Championship.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-county-championship] Leicestershire won their first Championship title.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The **1975 Cricket World Cup Final** was a One Day International cricket match played at Lord's, London, on 21 June 1975 to determine the winner of the 1975 Cricket World Cup.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] It was the second time that the West Indies and Australia had met in the tournament, after playing against each other in the group stage.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The West Indies won the match by 17 runs to claim their first title.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] West Indies qualified for the knockouts with a first-place finish in Group B.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The team won all three of their matches against Australia, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Then in the semi-final against New Zealand, the opposition opened brilliantly, but when Glenn Turner fell, the wickets tumbled the West Indies scored the required 158 to reach the final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia made it through to the knockouts in second place with their only loss being against the West Indies.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] But they did defeat Pakistan and Sri Lanka to take on England in the semi-final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Gary Gilmour took six wickets in the English innings to help them through to the final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The first final was played on 21 June (Midsummer of that year), a sunny day, in front of a capacity crowd of 26,765.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia won the toss and invited the West Indies to bat, hoping to make use of ideal bowling conditions.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The first moment of drama came when opener Roy Fredericks was dismissed hit wicket; he hooked a bouncer from Dennis Lillee for six, but in his follow-through lost his balance and knocked the bails off the stumps.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia were on top at 50/3 when West Indian captain Clive Lloyd came to the crease in partnership with veteran Rohan Kanhai.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The pair swung the match in the West Indies' favour by putting on 149 for the fourth wicket.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Kanhai played the anchor role – not scoring for 11 overs – while Lloyd took on the Australian bowling attack, surviving a dropped catch on 26 to score a century off 82 balls with 12 fours and two sixes, being dismissed shortly afterwards for 102.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Kanhai, in what would be his farewell from international cricket, scored an invaluable 55.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Solid contributions from Keith Boyce and Bernard Julien helped the West Indies close their innings at 291/8.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Burly left-arm seamer Gary Gilmour was the pick of the Australian bowlers with 5/48, backing up his strong semi-final performance.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The Australian run chase began steadily: at the 20-over mark, they were 80/1 with Alan Turner and captain Ian Chappell taking advantage of an easy pitch and fast outfield.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Then Viv Richards, who had failed with the bat, left his mark on the match with the next three run-outs.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] First he swooped in and dismissed Turner with a direct hit from close range, then Greg Chappell was also out with a direct hit after a slight misfield.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Doug Walters came in and helped his captain steady the ship.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia were at 162/3 with 21 overs remaining when Chappell, facing his opposing captain, pushed a ball to the left of mid-wicket and started off for a run.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] He hesitated initially when he saw Richards approaching but started off again after Richards fumbled the ball, only to be caught short of the crease by Richards' lightning recovery and return to Lloyd at the bowler's end.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] In each situation, the batsmen probably would have made the run had they not hesitated.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] When Lillee joined Jeff Thomson as last man in, Australia required 59 runs to win off seven overs.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The duo kept the game alive, putting on an unlikely last-wicket stand.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] With three overs remaining Lillee hit a no-ball to Fredericks at extra cover off Vanburn Holder and the crowd rushed on to the field oblivious to the umpire's call.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Amid the chaos, Fredericks attempted a run-out but missed and the ball disappeared into the crowd.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Lillee and Thomson kept running between the wickets until the crowd was dispersed.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] When play was resumed, the umpires decided to give Australia two runs.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] After protest from Thomson, they awarded three runs.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The match finally ended three balls later after Thomson had run a leg bye and Lillee scored a single.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The final wicket fell with Thomson swinging wildly and missing.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Having not realised the wicket-keeper had held the ball Thomson set off for a run, attempted to return after recognising his mistake but not before Murray knocked the bails off with a well-aimed underarm throw with his gloves on for a run-out.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The game ended at 8:43 pm after nearly 10 hours play.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Another pitch invasion ensued as the players and umpires ran for safety, with Thomson having his cricket pads stolen, Boyce losing his shoes and umpire Bird having his hat taken.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Bird later said that he came across the stolen hat being worn by a bus conductor in London a year after the event.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] When he asked about it, he was told by the conductor, who did not recognise Bird, that he'd "won the race" by sprinting onto the field at the final to take it.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The **1975 Cricket World Cup** (officially called the **Prudential Cup '75**) was the inaugural men's Cricket World Cup, and the first major tournament in the history of One Day International (ODI) cricket.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Organised by the International Cricket Conference (ICC), it took place in England, between 7 June and 21 June 1975.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was sponsored by Prudential Assurance Company and had eight participating countries: the six Test-playing teams of the time – Australia, England, India, New Zealand, Pakistan, the West Indies – and the two leading Associate nations at the time – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The teams were divided into two groups of four, with each team playing each other in their group once; the top two from each group qualified for the semi-finals, with the winners of these matches meeting in the final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match consisted of 60 overs per side and was played in traditional white clothing and with red balls; all were played and ended in daylight.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] England and New Zealand finished as the top two teams in Group A, while the West Indies finished top of the Group B table ahead of Australia as the four teams qualified through to the semi-finals.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia defeated England and the West Indies defeated New Zealand in the semi-finals, the West Indies which came into the tournament as favourites, defeated Australia in the final at Lord's by 17 runs to become the first World Cup winners.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] New Zealand batsman, Glenn Turner was the top run-scorer for the tournament with 333 runs, whilst Australian bowler Gary Gilmour was the top wicket-taker with 11 wickets despite only playing in the final two matches.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first multilateral cricket competition at international level was the 1912 Triangular Tournament in England.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was played between the three test nations at the time – England, Australia and South Africa.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The concept was later dropped because of inclement weather and a lack of public interest.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first one-day match to occur was in 1962 when four English county cricket teams filled in a gap to play in a limited overs knockout competition.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was won by Northamptonshire who defeated Leicestershire by five wickets.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The limited-over format had been used in what sponsors marketed as a 'World Cricket Cup' in England in 1966 and 1967, contested between England, a Rest of the World XI, and a touring team (the West Indies in 1966 and Pakistan in 1967).
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The marketing of the event was clearly influenced by the hosting of the 1966 FIFA World Cup in the same country.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The 1966 'World Cricket Cup' was won by England, that in 1967 by the Rest of the World.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] A report in the *Cricketer* implied that the last such match in this "Triangular Tournament", between Pakistan and the Rest of the World was neither well-attended nor taken entirely seriously: "It was a pity that a larger crowd was not present ...
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Sobers took the Cup and the World Xl took the gold medals.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was not until 1971 that the first official One Day International (ODI) took place at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG) as a replacement for the third test of the 1970–71 Ashes series between Australia and England.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to a deluge of rain that had affected the match for the first three days of the test.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match was a forty over match with each over being eight deliveries.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] After England made 190 from 39.4 overs, Australia chased the target at a steady rate to secure the match with 42 balls remaining.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Two years later at Lord's during the 1973 Women's Cricket World Cup, plans were made for a men's tournament to take place in 1975.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was planned to involve all the Test nations at the time in two group stages with the top two in each group qualifying for the knockout stage with the final at Lord's.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The format of the 1975 Cricket World Cup had the eight teams split into two groups of four, with each team playing the others in their group once.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played over 60 overs per side with group stage matches scheduled to take place between 7 and 14 June.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played entirely during day, with a cut off time of 7.30 pm.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Three days were allocated to each match with each able to be continued if they were halted for rain or bad light.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group advanced to the semi-finals on 18 June, with the winners qualifying for the final at Lord's on 21 June.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight teams were invited to compete at the World Cup: the six full members of the International Cricket Conference (ICC), and two other teams – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] South Africa was not allowed to complete due to the sporting boycott of the country which took place during apartheid era, the ICC having placed a moratorium on tours of the country in 1970.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began the teams were split into two groups.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The ICC made the decision to place the two teams which were not Test playing countries in separate groups.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] They also decided to place England and Australia in separate groups and to do the same with India and Pakistan.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Six grounds were used to host matches during the tournament.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The announcement of venues began on 26 July 1973 when the ICC announced that the tournament would be played, with Lord's as the venue for the final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The remaining venues were announced on 5 November 1974, with the scheduling for the tournament announced alongside that for the five county cricket tournaments that would take place during the 1975 season.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Other than Lord's, which hosted only one group stage match, and The Oval which hosted three, each of the grounds was used for two matches during the group stage.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Headingley and The Oval were the grounds chosen for the two semi-finals.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began each team named a squad of 14 players.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Heading into the first Cricket World Cup, the Ladbrokes betting agency had the West Indies as the favourites at 9–4.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was followed by England at 11–4 with Pakistan and Australia in third and fourth respectively.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] East Africa was last in the betting odds at 1500–1.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the tournament, most of the teams played in warm-up matches against English county teams to get used to the English conditions with most of the national teams getting wins.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only East Africa, Sri Lanka and India lost at least one warm-up match before the tournament.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia played in Canada, losing to Eastern Canada and drawing with Toronto, before heading to England.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight days before the World Cup, the ICC declared in a unanimous decision that any of the balls that went over a batsman's head would be called wide due to the fast short-pitched bowling.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The opening round of matches took place on 7 June with four matches being played.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match at Lord's saw England deliver the highest score by a team in the 60 over match with 334 runs being scored.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Dennis Amiss top scored for the English with 137 from 147 balls helped by Keith Fletcher and Chris Old who each recorded a half-century.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Sunil Gavaskar batted through the entire innings for only 36 runs off 174 balls, prompting Gulabrai Ramchand to speculate that he was treating the match as batting practice.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia opened their campaign with a win against Pakistan at Headingley with a 73-run victory.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to Dennis Lillee's five-wicket haul which brought Pakistan's hope of a win crashing down as they collapsed from 181 for four to be all out for 205.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Earlier, Ross Edwards top scored for Australia with 80 as he aided the Australians in getting 94 runs from the last 13 overs to bring Australia to 278 for seven from their 60 overs.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other two matches saw easy wins for the West Indies and New Zealand.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Glenn Turner, he occupied the crease during the whole New Zealand innings as he top scored with 171 as New Zealand won by 181 runs over East Africa.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies took a nine-wicket victory over Sri Lanka who became the first team to score under 100 runs in a One Day International.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Despite missing two players due to operation – Asif Iqbal – and examinations – Imran Khan – Pakistan was not fazed by the missing players in the second round of games with the team scoring 266 for seven from their 60 overs with standing captain Majid Khan top scoring for Pakistan with 60.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies fell to 166 for eight which included a period of three wickets for only 10 runs as Bernard Julien, Clive Lloyd and Keith Boyce all losing their wickets.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] But the last wicket pair of Deryck Murray and Andy Roberts stole the match away as the West Indies won by a wicket off the final over.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] On the field, Alan Turner scored a century as Australia ended with 328 with Sri Lanka falling 52 runs short as John Mason from *The Daily Telegraph* stated that they might not have many new admirers with their short ball stuff sending two Sri Lankan batsman to hospital.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Group A saw two convincing wins to England and India.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] At Trent Bridge, Keith Fletcher top scored for England with 131 as he guided the English to their second victory and going to the lead of the group table with an 80-run win over New Zealand.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other match in Group A saw 720 spectators observe India record a 10-wicket victory with Madan Lal taking three wickets for India, after East Africa were all-out for only 120.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the match sold out four days in advance, the West Indies took on Australia to see who would finish top of Group B.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the ball swinging in the air, the pair of Rod Marsh and Ross Edwards guided Australia to 192 with a 99-run partnership for the sixth wicket after Australia fell to 61/5.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies went on to take a seven-wicket victory with Alvin Kallicharran top scoring with 78, which included a period of 31 runs of nine Dennis Lillee deliveries as the West Indies finished top of Group B.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan ended their tournament with a 192-run victory over Sri Lanka at Trent Bridge with half centuries to Zaheer Abbas, Majid Khan and Sadiq Mohammad.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In Group A, New Zealand sealed their spot in the semi-finals with a four-wicket victory over India off the back of a century from Glenn Turner as he hit twelve fours on his way to an unbeaten innings of 114.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only Ramesh Sethi offered much resistance, lasting for 32 overs to score 30.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The knockout stage of the Cricket World Cup consisted of two single-elimination rounds leading to a final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] If the match was delayed due to rain there were two reserve days to play out the match.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first semi-final was between England and Australia at Headingley.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Australia, their one change in bringing in Gary Gilmour for Ashley Mallett proved critical in booking Australia's spot into the final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to the grassy pitch that both captains would criticise after the match.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia elected to field first, Gilmour took six wickets for 14 runs as he had England at 37 for seven after he bowled his 12 overs.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Mike Denness attempted to bring England back but would lose his wicket as England fell for 93.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In the run-chase, Australia collapsed to 39 for six before Gilmour partnered with Doug Walters as they chased the remaining runs to earn Australia a berth in the final.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The second semi-final was between the West Indies and New Zealand at The Oval.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Batting first, New Zealand reached 92 for only one loss at the lunch break.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] After lunch though, they collapsed to 158 with Geoff Howarth top scoring for New Zealand with 51, while Bernard Julien was the top wicket taker with four wickets.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The final match on 21 June was sold out three days beforehand.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the West Indies being favourites for the match, they were asked by Ian Chappell to bat first and would go on to score 291 for eight wickets from 60 overs.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] After being given a second chance from a Ross Edwards dropped chance at mid-wicket, Clive Lloyd went on to top score for the West Indies with 102.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Gary Gilmour was the best of the Australian bowlers with five wickets for 48 runs.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Ian Chappell scored a half-century to set up the foundation for Australia before three run-outs from the hands of Viv Richards put the pressure on Australia as they collapsed to 233 for nine.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] A final-wicket partnership of 41 from Dennis Lillee and Jeff Thomson brought Australia within 18 runs of victory.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] But a fifth run-out of the innings saw Australia bowled out for 274 and would see the West Indies win by 17 runs, claiming the first men's World Cup.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Glenn Turner of New Zealand ended the tournament as the leading run scorer for the 1975 edition with his 333 runs coming in four games which included an unbeaten 171 against East Africa, which was also the highest score of the tournament.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In second place was English player Dennis Amiss with Pakistan's Majid Khan rounding out the top three.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australian player Gary Gilmour was the tournament's leading wicket taker with 11 wickets from his two games, which included the best tournament figures in the semi-finals when he took six wickets for 14 against England.
[src:1975-cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Bernard Julien and Keith Boyce (both from the West Indies) finished in second place, both getting 10 wickets for the tournament.
